<header><h1>How Debt Settlement <span class="accent">Actually</span> Works</h1><p class="subtitle">The process, the timeline, and what the ads conveniently leave out.</p></header>
<div class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a> &rsaquo; How Settlement Works</div>
<main id="main-content">
  <div class="content-section"><h2>The Process Step by Step</h2><ol><li><strong>Consultation:</strong> You call a settlement company. They review your debts and promise to "settle for pennies on the dollar."</li><li><strong>Enrollment:</strong> You sign a contract enrolling your debts. Typical minimum is $10,000-$15,000 in <a href="https://creditcarddebtbankruptcy.org/" title="unsecured debt">unsecured debt</a>.</li><li><strong>Stop paying creditors:</strong> The company instructs you to stop making payments to your credit cards and instead deposit money into a dedicated savings account each month.</li><li><strong>Wait and save:</strong> For 12-36 months per account, your money accumulates while your accounts go delinquent, your credit score drops, and creditors call demanding payment.</li><li><strong>Negotiate:</strong> When enough money accumulates, the company contacts each creditor to negotiate a lump-sum payoff - typically 40-60% of the balance.</li><li><strong>Pay and repeat:</strong> Settled accounts are paid. The company takes their fee (15-25% of the original enrolled amount). Repeat for each creditor.</li></ol></div>
  <div class="content-section"><h2>What They Do Not Tell You in the Consultation</h2><ul><li><strong>Your credit score will tank.</strong> You are deliberately defaulting on every enrolled account. Each one goes 30, 60, 90, 120+ days delinquent.</li><li><strong>Creditors will call constantly.</strong> The company cannot make them stop. There is no <a href="https://automaticstay.org" title="Automatic Stay in Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project" target="_blank" rel="noopener">automatic stay</a>.</li><li><strong>Creditors can sue you.</strong> And many do. If a creditor sues and gets a judgment, they can garnish your wages.</li><li><strong>The savings account is not protected.</strong> Unlike <a href="https://bankruptcyexemptionsbystate.com/" title="exemptions">exempt property</a> in bankruptcy, creditors can levy your settlement savings account.</li><li><strong>Interest and fees keep accruing.</strong> Your $30,000 in debt can become $40,000 while you wait for settlements.</li></ul><div class="warning-box"><p><strong>The dropout problem:</strong> Industry data shows that 50-70% of people who enroll in settlement programs drop out before completing. They leave with damaged credit, accumulated fees, and balances higher than when they started.</p></div></div>
  <div class="content-section"><h2>Why Bankruptcy Is Different</h2><p>Bankruptcy provides what settlement cannot: legal protection. The <a href="https://automaticstay.org">automatic stay</a> stops all collection the moment you file. No more calls. No lawsuits. No garnishments. And at the end, the <a href="https://bankruptcydischarge.org/" title="discharge">discharge</a> eliminates the debt entirely - with no tax consequences. Settlement is a negotiation. Bankruptcy is a federal court order.</p></div>

